******
[1] USA
Date: Fri 4 Jan 2013
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research & Policy) News [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/general/news/jan0413flu.html


US flu activity continues to rise sharply
-----------------------------------------
Influenza activity continued its sharp rise through the last week of 2012, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said today [4 Jan 2012]. "Reports of influenza-like-illness (ILI) are nearing what have been peak levels during moderately severe seasons," said Joe Bresee, MD, chief of epidemiology and prevention in the CDC's flu division, in a CDC statement [http://www.cdc.gov/flu/spotlights/flu-activity-picks-up.htm] today.

The percentage of outpatient visits for ILI reported to the CDC's ILI network reached 5.6 percent for the week ending 29 Dec 2012 (week 52), up from 4.2 percent the week before and well above the national baseline of 2.2 percent. In the last moderately severe flu season, 2007-08, ILI activity peaked at 6.4 percent, in late February. By comparison, that marker reached 8.0 percent during the peak of the 2009 pandemic in October, according to CDC data.

As outlined in the agency's weekly FluView update, 31.6 percent of 9363 lab-tested respiratory specimens during week 52 were positive for flu, up from 29.6 percent the week before. That number approached 60 percent in midwestern states [see http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/].

41 states reported geographically widespread flu activity, 7 had regional activity, and one reported sporadic activity. During the previous week, 31 states reported widespread flu activity. The H3N2 strain -- typically associated with more-severe seasons -- continued to dominate, constituting 1209 (98 percent) of 1234 influenza A viruses that were subtyped, with the other 2 percent being pandemic 2009 H1N1. All told, 79 percent of flu viruses tested were type A and 21 percent type B. The circulating strains continue to be well matched to the strains in the flu vaccine, and no resistance to antiviral drugs has been detected, the CDC said. 2 new pediatric flu deaths were reported, bringing the season total to 18.

"While we can't say for certain how severe this season will be, we can say that a lot of people are getting sick with influenza and we are getting reports of severe illness and hospitalizations," Bresee said, adding, "Anyone who has not already been vaccinated should do so now."

[Byline: Jim Wappes)

