[The information above is supplemented by table and diagrams. Interested readers should consult the original documents via the source URLs above to view these tables and diagrams.

ProMED-mail is supplementing the above with the following additional information describing the current situation in Norway, translated from a Norwegian newspaper by Dr Peter Andras Csango.

"At the beginning of the entrance to the new influenza season, the laboratory reports are at a level that indicates low influenza activity. Last week [week ending 30 Dec 2012], of the 590 samples analyzed 4 influenza A viruses and 3 influenza B viruses were detected. 2 of last week's influenza A viruses were A(H1N1)pdm09, the other 2 have not been subtyped yet. Earlier this fall [2012], most surveyed A virus was A(H3N2). The hitherto studied 3 influenza B viruses belong to the Yamagata [lineage], as do most B viruses in recent months. There were fewer influenza A cases than in the previous week, when most came from hospitalized patients at a single hospital. Otherwise the incidence appears to be on the same level as in the previous week."

Overall there are differences currently in the frequencies of the A and B strains circulating in Europe and North America, but the outbreak strains are still all well-matched with the current northern hemisphere vaccine. It will be interesting to observe to what extent this close-matching will have on the severity and course of the developing global epidemic, in comparison with previous years. - Mod.CP]
